description: Unknown; likely from a Pama-Nyungan language. English sources from the 19th century describe it as an Australian word.

entries.meaning: (Australia) A coastal sea squirt, Pyura stolonifera, found in some parts of Australia and South Africa.
examples: All along our coast, cunjevoi are destroyed by fishermen, who use them for bait and, as a result, the other animals and plants that live in association with them are also killed.

description: Uncertain; likely from Bandjalang kanjibuy, or from another Pama-Nyungan language. Attested in English from the 19th century.

entries.meaning: A large flowering plant, Alocasia macrorrhizos, native to tropical islands from Asia to Australia.
